<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFWeismann1993">Weismann, M. M. (1993). "The epidemiology of personality disorders. A 1990 update.". <i>Journal of Personality Disorders</i> (Spring issue, Suppl.): 44–62.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=The+epidemiology+of+personality+disorders.+A+1990+update.&amp;rft.jtitle=Journal+of+Personality+Disorders&amp;rft.aulast=Weismann&amp;rft.aufirst=M.+M.&amp;rft.au=Weismann%2C+M.+M.&amp;rft.date=1993&amp;rft.issue=Spring+issue%2C+Suppl.&amp;rft.pages=44%E2%80%9362&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Schizoid_personality_disorder"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span>. As an interesting comment on the usual low-prevalence figures for this disorder, Philip Manfield in <i>Split Self, Split Object</i>, Arenson (1992) states that "I believe that the schizoid condition is far more common..... comprising perhaps as many as 40 percent of all personality disorders. This huge discrepancy is probably largely because someone with a schizoid disorder is less likely to seek treatment than someone with other axis-II disorders." p.204. Manfield backs this claim with a study by Valliant &amp; Drake (1985) who found the over 40% of a particular sample group of inner city males were schizoid.</li>
